[normal]2.3 This was the first
[normal] warning that the threat to the airport's
[normal] 
[normal]operations
[normal] 
[normal]was from severe flooding
[normal] 
[normal]as well as
[normal] 
[normal]high winds. This obviously
[normal] 
[normal]requires a very different sort of contingency planning. Overnight rainfall of over
[normal] 
[normal]68mm in the area significantly
[normal] 
[normal]exceeded Met Office foreca
[normal]sts causing the worst flooding in the airport's living memory.
[normal]2.4 Gatwick issued its first passenger communications via twitter at 4:29am about possible
[normal]      
[normal]disruption.
[normal]2.5
[normal] 
[normal]As
[normal] 
[normal]a
[normal] 
[normal]result
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]rain
[normal] 
[normal]two
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]six
[normal] 
[normal]switch-rooms
[normal] 
[normal]located
[normal] 
[normal]in
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]North
[normal] 
[normal]Terminal
[normal] 
[normal]flooded,
[normal] 
[normal]knocking
[normal] 
[normal]out 
[normal]much
[normal] 
[normal]of
[normal] 
[normal]the
[normal] 
[normal]power.
[normal]2.6 Simultaneously on the airfield three substations flooded and the Runway Instrument Landing System was
[normal] 
[normal]disabled. This is a known
[normal] 
[normal]and understood risk and the contingency
[normal] 
[normal]worked with the backup generators kicking 
[normal]in to provide
[normal] 
[normal]continuity of power.
[normal] 
[normal]The South Terminal continued
[normal] 
[normal]to operate as normal and the airfield remained operational throughout.
[normal]2.7 However by 7:30am it was clear that the damage to the North Terminal switch-room
[normal] 
[normal]was severe and 
[normal]that 
[normal]full power
[normal] 
[normal]would
[normal] not be reinstated to the North Terminal on Christmas Eve.
[normal]2.8
[normal] 
[normal]By
[normal] 
[normal]9:00am
[normal] 
[normal]we
[normal] 
[normal]had
[normal] 
